{"cursor":"9649","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nIn meteorology, 'visibility' is a measure of the distance at which an object or\nlight can be clearly discerned. It is reported within surface weather\nobservations and METAR code either in meters or statute miles, depending upon\nthe country. Visibility affects all forms of traffic: roads, sailing and\naviation. Meteorological visibility refers to transparency of air: in dark,\nmeteorological visibility is still the same as in daylight for the same air.\n","linknr":256,"url":"Visibility","recorded":1362553500,"links":41,"instances":["tires","vision","electromagnetic_radiation"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Visibility|","Basic meteorological concepts and phenomena"],"headings":["Definition","Derivation","Fog, mist, and haze","Very low visibility","Low visibility warnings","Visibility and air pollution","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Text_document_with_red_question_mark.svg/40px-Text_document_with_red_question_mark.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9f/Plane_flying_into_clouds.jpg/150px-Plane_flying_into_clouds.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/Foggy_morning_road_-_visibility_at_200_ft.jpg/250px-Foggy_morning_road_-_visibility_at_200_ft.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/Tel_Aviv_Carmel_Panorama.jpg/240px-Tel_Aviv_Carmel_Panorama.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/c/4/4c450ee128305ac9118ff2f1c1d25b39.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/f/5/2f59f6460b02f0b383e679400ae483b0.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/d/e/5de6bedd7bc013be75b3211658e88eea.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/c/2/9c2a2035d42d14a19ae381698a466134.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/